***(Rewritten-needs final edit)***

Have you told yourself, “This is the last time,” one too many times? Maybe you find yourself stepping over the line, even when you know exactly what the consequences will be. It is easy to become convinced that the only way to find comfort, control, or peace lies in the very behavior you are hopelessly trying to stop. Compulsive habits range from the obvious to the almost undetectable. Whether it is pornography, alcohol, substances, gambling, or endless scrolling, you feel trapped in a cycle that includes despair, frustration, numbness, or shame.

## What's actually going on

If you have spent any time in nature you likely have seen a deer path in the woods. These paths are well worn, trampled, and have served as a familiar passageway to the animals that have become reliant upon them.

In a similar way, our brain builds neural pathways of familiarity. When a person first uses a substance or engages in a behavior (like gambling, scrolling, or pornography), the brain releases a flood of dopamine. A new path is created. Faint at first, over time the path becomes well-worn, accessible, instinctive. The initial engagement may have been an effort to find comfort, gain control, or numb pain, but those promises are eventually revealed to be superficial and not enough.

We are however, body *and* soul. There are clear environmental and physiological factors at play, but there are also deeper spiritual implications involved in all behavior including those behaviors that feel unmanageable and unwanted.

A biblical worldview acknowledges that upbringing, brain chemistry, and trauma heavily shape our behavior, but it also points to a deeper root cause for our struggles. At our core, we possess a natural inclination toward rebellion from a holy God, a reflection of our fallen nature. Substances and behaviors have replaced God as our primary source of comfort, control, escape. The reality of sin is that it is a cruel master.

## How counseling helps

Sometimes we walk habitual "deer paths" so long that we lose sight of our own patterns. To break the cycle, we must expose the empty promises of compulsive habits as a form of misdirected worship. Counseling helps you recognize your triggers, identify faulty worldviews, and find true rest in God. Together, we will reconcile who you are today with who God created you to be, empowering you to walk in alignment with His truth.

## When to reach out

If you're tired of the cycle, not just the consequences, but the cycle itself, that's enough. You don't have to hit a dramatic bottom to start counseling.
